# debug/ â€” In-Game Light Authoring Overlay

The `debug/` folder contains a **debug-only authoring tool** (excluded from release builds).
It provides a floating-label HUD over nearby light entities so a developer can identify,
inspect, and live-edit light parameters without leaving the game.

## File structure

| File                           | Role                                                                                                                                                                |
| ------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `lightLabels.ws`               | Entry point: `@addField`/`@addMethod` on `CR4Player`; wires input to the manager, editor, and accelerator                                                           |
| `LRDebug_LabelManager.ws`      | Scans for nearby lights, owns the current target, coordinates attribute adjustment and rewriter toggling                                                            |
| `LRDebug_AttributeEditor.ws`   | Owns the selected attribute index and all per-attribute edit logic (ID, label, step, clamp, delta)                                                                  |
| `LRDebug_AdjustAccelerator.ws` | Tracks burst-input timing and returns an acceleration multiplier                                                                                                    |
| `LRDebug_LightOneLiner.ws`     | Floating-text label for a single light entity (statemachine)                                                                                                        |
| `LRDebug_ToastOneLiner.ws`     | Short-lived floating toast message                                                                                                                                  |
| `LRDebug_EntityUtils.ws`       | Shared free functions: `LRDebug_FindNearbyLights`, `LRDebug_FirstPointLight`, `LRDebug_FirstSpotLight`, `LRDebug_IsCandle`, `LRDebug_EnsureEntityHasRewriter`, etc. |

## External dependency

Requires `mod_sharedutils_oneliners` (external mod, not in this repo) which provides the
`SU_Oneliner` base class used for all floating-text overlays.

## How it works

### Scanning and labels

- A 0.25-second repeating timer (`LRDebug_RefreshOnelinersTimer`) calls
  `lrDebugLabelManager.Scan()` each tick.
- `Scan()` finds nearby `CGameplayEntity` instances that own at least one
  `CPointLightComponent` or `CSpotLightComponent`.
- Normal range: 10 m. Focus Mode (Witcher Senses) range: 25 m.
- Each qualifying entity gets one `LRDebug_LightOneLiner` for its lifetime
  (statemachine; `Idle` â†” `FollowEntity`). The object is reused â€” it is never
  destroyed and recreated while the entity stays in range.
- Markup is generated once at creation and **only** recomputed on explicit events
  (attribute cycle, path-label toggle, highlight change). The timer does no markup
  work per tick.

### Target selection

Each timer tick, the entity most directly in front of the camera (highest dot-product
against camera direction, minimum 0.6 threshold) is selected as the label manager's
`target` and highlighted with red markers. Only one entity is targeted at a time.
The previous target's highlight is cleared before the new one is set.

### Live attribute editing

13 attributes are editable on the targeted entity, all managed by `LRDebug_AttributeEditor`:

| Group       | Attributes                                                   |
| ----------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| Light shape | `brightness`, `radius`, `attenuation`                        |
| Shadow      | `shadowFadeDistance`, `shadowFadeRange`, `shadowBlendFactor` |
| Colour      | `overrideColour`, `colourR`, `colourG`, `colourB`            |
| Rewriter    | `useSpotlightColor`, `alignPointLights`, `alignOffsetZ`      |

- **Cycle** through attributes via `LRDebug_CycleAttrPrev` / `LRDebug_CycleAttrNext`
  (calls `lrDebugAttrEditor.CycleAttribute(Â±1)`).
- **Adjust** the selected attribute via `LRDebug_AdjustDown` â€” a single bidirectional
  binding (scroll wheel or analog axis). Positive `action.value` increments; negative
  decrements.
- **Step sizing** is dynamic: larger values use larger steps. Attributes with fixed
  fine-grained steps (`attenuation`, `shadowBlendFactor`, `alignOffsetZ`) always use
  0.05 steps regardless of value.
- **Acceleration**: holding a direction in tight bursts (â‰Ą 2 events within 75 ms each)
  triggers up to 8Ă— step multiplier. A direction reversal cuts the multiplier in half;
  a pause of > 500 ms resets it entirely.
- Large deltas are applied in sub-steps so they don't skip step-size thresholds.

### Edit state and application

- Edits accumulate in `entity.lrDebugTempParams` (`CLightRewriteSourceParams`), a
  volatile working copy **separate from the production params**. It resets on game load.
- `LRDebug_EnsureEntityHasRewriter` lazily creates an `ILightSourceRewriter` for an
  entity if it doesn't already have one (using existing config params or a temporary
  debug entry tagged `LR_DebugTemp`).
- After each adjustment, `rewriter.LRDebug_SetMenuOverrideParams(params)` +
  `rewriter.RewriteLight()` apply the change live in-game.
- `LRDebug_ToggleRewriter` (`inOriginalState` flag) lets the developer toggle the
  rewriter on/off to A/B the entity against its vanilla state. This is coordinated by
  `lrDebugLabelManager.ToggleRewriterOnTarget()`.

### Capturing values for production config

A log/output mechanism exists to extract the current `lrDebugTempParams` values so
they can be written into the production XML config. Values are not automatically
persisted â€” the developer must trigger this output and transfer them manually.

## Fields added via @addField

| Class                  | Fields added                                                                                      |
| ---------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `CR4Player`            | `lrDebugLabels`, `lrDebugToast`, `lrDebugLabelManager`, `lrDebugAttrEditor`, `lrDebugAccelerator` |
| `CGameplayEntity`      | `lrdebugOneliner`, `lrDebugTempParams`                                                            |
| `ILightSourceRewriter` | `inOriginalState`                                                                                 |

## Input bindings (input.settings)

```
IK_NumPad7=(Action=LRDebug_ToggleLabels)
IK_NumPad8=(Action=LRDebug_ToggleLabelPaths)
```

Additional bindings (`LRDebug_CycleAttrPrev`, `LRDebug_CycleAttrNext`,
`LRDebug_AdjustDown`, `LRDebug_ToggleRewriter`) require separate input.settings entries.

## Key design invariants to preserve

- **Do not recompute markup on the refresh timer.** Markup is only rebuilt on explicit
  state changes to keep the tick path cheap.
- **`lrDebugTempParams` is the working edit state.** It is not the production
  `params` object â€” edits here do not affect the config system directly.
- **One oneliner per entity, reused.** Do not create a new `LRDebug_LightOneLiner`
  for an entity that already has one in `entity.lrdebugOneliner`.
- **`LRDebug_IsCandle` determines spotlight vs point light source** when reading the
  initial light value for an entity. This is the current heuristic; extend it if new
  entity types need different source-light selection logic.
- **`lightLabels.ws` is a thin wiring layer only.** All domain logic lives in the
  dedicated classes. The player methods should do nothing more than delegate to the
  manager, editor, and accelerator.
